.TH _PRINTF 3 "November 2025" "Holberton School â€“ Custom Printf" "Library Functions Manual"

.SH NAME
_printf \- custom implementation of the standard printf function

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #include "main.h"
.sp
.B int _printf(const char *format, ...);

.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B _printf()
function produces output according to a format string and a variable
list of arguments. It is a simplified re-implementation of the standard
C library
.B printf(3)
function, supporting a selected set of conversion specifiers.

The
.I format
string contains ordinary characters, which are written as-is, and
conversion directives which begin with the '%' character and determine
how subsequent arguments are formatted.

This implementation does \fInot\fR support flags, field width, precision,
or length modifiers.

.SH SUPPORTED CONVERSION SPECIFIERS

.TP
.B %c
Prints a single character.

.TP
.B %s
Prints a null-terminated string.
If the argument is NULL, the string "(null)" is printed.

.TP
.B %%
Prints a literal '%' character.

.TP
.B %d, %i
Prints a signed decimal integer.

.TP
.B %u
Prints an unsigned decimal integer.

.TP
.B %o
Prints an unsigned integer in octal notation (base 8).

.TP
.B %x
Prints an unsigned integer in lowercase hexadecimal.

.TP
.B %X
Prints an unsigned integer in uppercase hexadecimal.

.TP
.B %b
Prints an unsigned integer in binary (base 2).

.TP
.B %S
Prints a string.
Non-printable characters (ASCII < 32 or >= 127) are printed in the form:
.RS
\fB\\xHH\fR
.RE
where \fBHH\fR is the uppercase two-digit hexadecimal code.

.TP
.B %p
Prints a pointer address in lowercase hexadecimal, prefixed with "0x".
If the pointer is NULL, "(nil)" is printed.

.SH BUFFERED OUTPUT
All character output uses the internal
.B _putchar()
function, which stores characters in a static 1024-byte buffer.
The buffer is automatically flushed when full.
At the end of execution,
.B _printf()
forces a flush by calling:
.RS
_putchar(-1);
.RE

Using a local buffer minimizes the number of system calls to
.BR write (2),
improving performance.

.SH RETURN VALUE
The
.B _printf()
function returns the total number of characters printed.
If an error occurs, or if the format string is NULL or invalid
(e.g., a trailing '%'), the function returns \-1.

.SH EXAMPLES

.TP
Print a string:
.RS
_printf("Hello %s!\\n", "World");
.RE

.TP
Print numbers:
.RS
_printf("Dec: %d Hex: %x Bin: %b\\n", 255, 255, 255);
.RE

.TP
Custom %S:
.RS
_printf("%S\\n", "Best\\nSchool");
.br
Output: Best\\x0ASchool
.RE

.TP
Pointer:
.RS
_printf("Address: %p\\n", ptr);
.RE

.SH SEE ALSO
.BR printf(3),
.BR write(2),
.BR stdarg(3)

.SH AUTHOR
Custom implementation written by Randa Baeshen and Norah Aljuhani for the Holberton School printf project.
